wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#d7c6e6;strokeColor=#6a3fa0;fontColor=#2c1650;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="1060" y="956" width="251" height="108" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Person-affecting&lt;br&gt;view&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+4+6+10]&lt;br&gt;→ The Humane League&lt;br&gt;(Jan Narveson, Melinda Roberts)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + no_discounting_future_humans + suffering_focused + person_affecting_view&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Person-affecting population ethics: making happy people is neutral, so the astronomical case for x-risk reduction — which rests on the sheer number of extra future lives saved from extinction — loses almost all its force. Only the harm to people who exist regardless still counts. This is the standard premise longtermism&#x27;s critics deny (discussed as the key objection in Greaves &amp; MacAskill&#x27;s &#x27;The Case for Strong Longtermism&#x27;). It requires no_discounting_future_humans, the astronomical-stakes move it pushes back on. || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 4 no_discounting_future_humans → 6 suffering_focused → 10 person_affecting_view" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJzFWf1v2zgS%2FVeIoMXZaWRLTtI0KfJDPpy2aNrNxtlm75rCpSXa4loSVZKKonbTv%2F0eKcnfTpMDFlegqCuTM2%2BGM28e5R8bARvSLNInImAbBxvtNjk8PCRXkvKEaEF8Sb8X%2BJAn5CbruN4OyYWMglvOcpJ7%2FU5%2Fu7%2FTf9n3XNJQWqTEc5vGwE0CQ0dKZXGquUiIH8LeAXFJSqXwQ04jY87b7xCPDKns05wW%2FTCLaaLqLzqEJjymkeorEbM8pLr%2BZpsMM51JVm3ox1RrJvs512E%2F4MoXWaJ5MqqX75BEzD7vz%2B2uV70kKhsOmbQLhJ8pFkwgAjaTSiR9ihW%2BtWESYIPsUj8kdBopV4SSi0KH%2BDzkESPI4%2FRr1SbaREKDQG0RyZB8njBFhLTGJHOQIBozxMMVnuuQlbn7l0LQiW9tvCa%2BiFOhTIyTBdibBAwW8Ygra01pmgQ0EgkjMU43apGvk8Pr3n41UM12dpciKGy8pVHGiBhaC9Nzblljx0xpMsgKkhk3ZqNis4EdkCvYemtyysg5o6OMlRvfdD92L4%2BuuqdkUJARS5ikmrXSoq4nFnA9l6FNfLmFM9MlDpNEWLK2%2Fkh8JrWJNhYSNTRJlirXlpmgaRpxplqkV8StSIwSI